#Jack_sloper_Nimely Known As 'Master T.' Is a Liberian Afropop Artist Born In Bomi County Tubmanburg. He Started His Career In 2001 And He Later Went To Ghana October 16, 2001. Master T. Did His First Single At Nana King Studio In Accra Ghana Titled "Picture Me Lonely", After Recording This song, He later Traveled To Lagos Nigeria In January 11, 2002, Doing a Single With Top Producer #Steve_Tequah Titled "Baby Love". Master T Later Returned To Ghana And Decided To Do An Album At Signford Studio. Due To Some Miss Understanding With The Studio Manager, The Album Wasn't Completed. July 3, 2006, Happily, Master_T Returned To His Motherland Liberia Where He Met Top Promoter DJ_TK Lamont "L.I.B finest" and Begin To Promote His Songs As Well As Connecting Him With #Smooth_The_Kalokalo_Man. It Was During That Time Smooth Was About To Lunch His Kakalo Album. Master_T Did His First Performance On Smooth Show, Song Tagged: "Kolo". At the End Of 2006, Mater_T Recorded a lot Of Songs At #D_Boy Studio Tagged "I like that girl", "Life" And "African Lady". After Recording a lot Of Songs With In Liberia, Mater_T Departed In 2007 Traveling To Sierra Leone With #Smooth_The_Kolokalo_Man To Perform On Sierra Leone Independence Day. With Passion And Effort To The Music Game, In 2013 Mater_T Was Officially Signed To #T_Bund_Studio And He Recorded Eight (8) Songs. in 2015 #T_Bund_Studio Hosted a Show At Miami Beach In Monrovia Where He Did Perform. In 2016, Master_T Contract With #T_Bund_Studio Ended Which Led Him To Be An Independent Artist. With all these Constraints He Went Through, In 2018 He Did a Single With #Stone_Luck_Shine. In 2018 Again He Did Record Another Single With #Master_LZEE. Master_T Is Now Working With a Movie Production House called #Team_Liberia_International The young And Talented Master_T Did a New Single With #Master_Lzee Song Title "Suitable" This Year (2020). The Artist Is Independent And Will Be Looking Forward To a Management Team. Keep Following us @FrontPage_Liberiaüá±üá∑üá±üá∑ Front Page Liberia

message: Hey Clemson Tigers! An organization in our community needs our help! Clemson Paw Partners is nonprofit that deals with the abused and neglected animals in Pickens County and works to lessen the overpopulation of animals through spay-neuter surgeries. In May of 2020, Pickens County Council leased Clemson Paw Partners a building in Central next to the library to operate a low cost spay-neuter clinic offering surgeries at less than $100. This will be the only clinic of its kind in S.C. to offer this service at such a low cost! Through the provision of this service the Clemson area will reduce the population of homeless animals and reduce animal starvation. However, they need our help in raising money in order to open their facility and any little bit helps! If you are interested in donating you can go to their website, http://clemsonpawpartners.org, or Venmo them @pawpartner-18. One they open they will also be looking for volunteers from the Animal sciences program either at Clemson or Tri-County!

message: If you‚Äôve been in Clemson, you‚Äôve probably seen a sit-in taking place in front of Sikes Hall. The sit-in, organized by Clemson Students for Survivors, a coalition of more than 30 student organizations, was created to advocate for more resources for survivors of interpersonal violence. Check out what some of the organizers had to say about the sit-in and then head the link in the comments to read the full story. The sit-in is continuing indefinitely as of Tuesday, Oct. 27 with virtual events being held on rainy days, and conversations between the organizers and Clemson administration are ongoing. The Tiger will continue reporting on updates regarding the sit-in and the Clemson Students for Survivors coalition. Updates can be found on our website.

message: Hey! This student organization Tuesday, let‚Äôs talk about Clemson Makerspace! The Clemson Makerspace is a team dedicated to the quality and service of students. All of their technology available is free for students to use, and the staff is here to help. What started as a simple idea back in the Fall of 2015, has blossomed into an environment that fosters collaboration and creativity across all majors. They offer students technology to create anything they might dream up. By providing training on the 3D printers and laser cutter housed in the space, the Makerspace enables even the most basic level beginners to use the resources. Although the staff has already seen this program expand tremendously since it initially began, they hope to see it continue to expand to more disciplines as they grow as a student organization. You can get involved by visiting their website!

message: Another Monday has almost come and gone for us, Tigers! Check out this article written by Anna Transou, Outlook Senior Staff Writer, about changing majors and how it changed her college career! The link is in the comments below. ‚ÄúChanging majors is an intimidating endeavor, but all of the effort was worth it in comparison to what would have been should I have stayed in the mind-numbing science classes that I tried forcing myself into taking. If you find yourself down a wrong path in your degree program, take a deep breath. No matter how far down it you‚Äôve traveled, I promise you, you can turn around, or at least take a detour by choosing a minor that captures you. The extra effort it takes to switch majors is 110% worth it as compared to forcing yourself to study things that you lack passion for. In this whole process, I‚Äôve been able to start living more for myself, and I‚Äôd advise anyone contemplating switching to make a change for yourself and take the risk.‚Äù

message: Forest officials on the Pomeroy Ranger District will reopen motorized access on Forest Service Roads (FSR) 47, 4712 and a portion of FSR 4713 on Saturday, Oct. 24. The Tucannon watershed experienced substantial road and trail damage from the February 2020 region-wide flooding across northeast Oregon and southeast Washington. Due to significant flood damage, long-term temporary closures along the Tucannon River were put in place until critical repairs could be completed. message: Coverage of weekly Board of Trustees meeting: MISSION ‚Äì The Board of Trustees (Board) for the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian Reservation (CTUIR) held their weekly Monday morning meeting June 6. Present at the meeting was Board Chair Kat Brigham, Vice Chair Aaron Ashley, Secretary Sally Kosey, General Council Chair Lindsey Watchman, Board members Lisa Ganuelas, Toby Patrick, Boots Pond and Corinne Sams. Treasurer Sandra Sampson was on travel. The Board passed an amended poll for resolution 22-046, approving a grant application for Cay-Uma-Wa Head Start. The date on the polled sheet was changed to May 26 from June 26. A motion to ratify the polled motion, with changes, was made by Sams and seconded by Pond, the motion passed 7-0-0. Under new business, resolution 22-047, a revision of the Nixyaawii Neighborhood Development Plan Cost was the first item on the agenda. A revision to the plan cost was shown in exhibit 1. The exhibit was confidential. Pond motioned to pass the resolution and the motion was seconded by Patrick before being passed 7-0-0 Resolution 22-048, which included a Timine Way North project contract cost price amendment, was next on the agenda. The price contract budget was in confidential exhibits 1c and 2. The resolution gave the Housing Department authority, in consultation with the Finance Department, to set adjusted rent amounts for the Timine North apartments. According to the sixth resolved, the Housing Department is responsible for administering the rental units. The resolved states rent adjustments will only be allowable to cover project debt service, operational maintenance and will be capped at five percent in a single year. The resolved also mandates residents be given 90-days-notice before each rent increase. Pond said during discussion that after the Board‚Äôs June 3 work session he asked that the tenant notice period be changed to 90 days from 30 days-notice, as suggested by staff initially. He said he had concerns about the notice period from his own experience living in apartments and the industry standard being closer to three months rather than one... Read the rest at: https://cuj.ctuir.org/2022/06/weekly-board-of-trustees-meeting-june-6/

message: This week we‚Äôre doing things a little different üëç Starting Monday we‚Äôre going to be sharing a new program, opportunity or event for you to grow your practice or personal self every day. In a perfect world, patients would be able to pay in full up front for all products and services. But the world is far from perfect, and today's economic challenges can be extremely prohibitive for our patients seeking care. Instead of putting yourself at risk by accepting partial payments and then being stuck eating the costs, we're learning about an excellent alternative that serves both doctors and patients from successful private practice owner Dr. Benjamin Thayil and Robert Nunziato of Sunbit.

From the outside looking in, Dr. Harbir Sian, Optometrist‚Äôs recent TEDx Talk probably looked like an amazing accomplishment by a doctor who has it all - the charisma, the platform, the knowledge, the confidence. But to get on that stage, did you know he had to overcome a lot of hard criticism just days before the live event, embrace the areas he could fix, and have confidence to still go out there when he was told ‚Äúit was too late to scrap the whole thing‚Äù. Reality bites, and it bites hard. But how you accept criticism: embrace people‚Äôs honesty, and know that when it stings that means that it‚Äôs probably something important for you to hear, that can shape a lot about the successes you will go on to achieve. And one other thing about criticism- you can take it in, but you still need to have the confidence in yourself to know when you‚Äôve done work you are proud of and you‚Äôre ready to share it. Check out the podcast to dive into a reflection on the pain and value of listening to those experts around you. https://defocusmedia.com/accepting-criticism/

message: In this week's episode, Dr. Howard Purcell answers all the tough questions. Drs. Darryl Glover and Howard Purcell discuss NECO‚Äôs Diversity & Inclusion Advisory Council, Warby Parker's scholarship to increase Black representation in optometry, and more. Tune in today at 6:00 PM EDT.

Dr. Janelle Davison noticed that one of the biggest hurdles to selling glasses in her private practice was how difficult insurance plans make the optical retail process. Patients and consumers hate to be "nickle and dimed" and with plans dictating every element of a patient's glasses with a copay or cost, it seemed impossible to simplify the process to a more patient-friendly option. Enter her brain child, Paradeyem Optical Software - a software that creates custom bundle packages built around insurance premiums so that you opticians can present a simple, packaged option at one price. The result: an increase in optical sales by 35%! Check out this podcast to learn more: https://defocusmedia.com/a-paradigm-shift-in-your-optical-retail%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC%EF%BF%BC/

message: Whether it‚Äôs outright physical inappropriateness or comments made in passing, dealing with sexual harassment in the workplace is very common. What‚Äôs worse, most victims don‚Äôt know what to do because they fear they are at risk of losing their jobs if they report the issue or even comment that it‚Äôs making them uncomfortable. Drs. Kate Hamm and Rachel Simpson go over some of the tips from author Meredith Holley‚Äôs book, Career Defense 101: How to Stop Sexual Harassment Without Quitting Your Job. Putting clear boundaries, following up with email, and creating a culture of accountability is just a few ways in this incredible book in the latest Lunch Date with Rachel and Kate podcast! Also don‚Äôt miss the chance to win your own audiobook copy narrated by Dr. Rachel Simpson herself. Just head over to the @rklunchdate Instagram account to enter! https://defocusmedia.com/lunch-date-with-rachel-kate-stop-sexual-harassment-without-quitting-your-job/

The Year of Vision has not been running exactly to plan for anyone in eye care, but for Ashley Mills, the CEO of The Vision Council, it has meant a complete restructuring of eyecare‚Äôs major spring and fall Vision Expo events and the need for new innovations and outreach to help ODs navigate not just COVID-19, but topics ranging from diversity in eyecare to consumer trends in optical. The Vision Council is an organization that brings the entire eyecare industry together: optometrists, opticians, frame designers, and industry members all connecting to shape the pulse of the industry. ‚ÄúWe think that vision matters,‚Äù Mills explains about the role of The Vision Council. ‚ÄúWe think it needs to be elevated. We think it impacts how people live their lives, and we want to the be the leader in making sure that people get the vision correction that they need to live their best lives. Vision is empowerment.‚Äù Check out the full story and interview on Optometry Times: https://www.optometrytimes.com/view/behind-the-data-in-eye-care-insights-from-the-vision-council-s-ashely-mills

The new FTC Contact Lens Rule went into effect 10/16, and we‚Äôre wondering how your office is handling the change? Have you made new office protocols? Printed new paperwork for patients to sign in office? Changes your intake forms for patients to electronically sign receipt of their contact lens prescription? Share what‚Äôs working for your practice!

If you‚Äôve ever looked around a conference or meeting or panel and felt, I don‚Äôt see anyone like me here, you aren‚Äôt alone! In 2019 The Vision Council conducted the first ever survey on diversity in the eyecare industry. What they found is that compared to the average U.S. workforce, the eyecare industry is 11 years older, has 6% fewer females, 6% less people of color, 12% less Hispanic, and 1% less people who identify as LGBTQ+. When it comes to senior leadership positions in the eyecare industry (owner, partner, C-level, president, director, executive vice president, senior vice president), compared to the average U.S. management level the eyecare industry is whiter and more male. Vision has 11% fewer women and 5% less people of color in senior management positions. So what can we do? Check out our podcast this week with Vision Council CEO Ashley Mills where she discussed the initiatives coming from this survey, including the foundation of the Diversity and Inclusion Task Force being led by Tarrence Lackran. https://www.optometrytimes.com/view/behind-the-data-in-eye-care-insights-from-the-vision-council-s-ashely-mills

Dr. Marguerite McDonald just might be the most famous eye doctor you‚Äôve ever known. Her pioneering work in refractive surgery led to modern day ablation. As an ophthalmologist in her 30s, she was the first doctor to conduct laser eye surgery on a human. She sits down with Dr. Chris Lievens on the latest 4 Eyed Professor Podcast to share her story and to talk about the current state of research being difficult for clinical physicians to pursue. https://defocusmedia.com/the-4-eyed-professor-dr-mcdonald-personal-history-and-experiences/

Hot compresses and dry eye: maybe they aren‚Äôt right for many of your patients?? If there is underlying ocular rosacea or active inflammation, adding heat can increase swelling and inflammation around the eye. On last weeks podcast Dr. Melanie Denton shares how heat masks and hot massages have become less and less a part of her dry eye practice and reducing inflammation with treatments like immunomodulation prescription eye drops and IPL treatments have become mainstays of her treatment strategy for many patients. https://defocusmedia.com/rx-dry-eye/
